WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: I.V.M.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: I.V.M.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.800
[Amit Varma]: And now let's move on to the show.

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:31.620
[Amit Varma]: When I was growing up in India in the 1980s, making phone calls wasn't the easiest thing

00:01:31.620 --> 00:01:32.620
[Amit Varma]: in the world.

00:01:32.620 --> 00:01:36.840
[Amit Varma]: The government had a monopoly on providing telephones, and the waiting list for a telephone

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:38.960
[Amit Varma]: could extend to five years or more.

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:43.240
[Amit Varma]: I was a privileged kid, my father was in the AIS, so we had a phone at home.

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:47.320
[Amit Varma]: But even for a privileged kid like me, air travel was a luxury.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:50.480
[Amit Varma]: You guessed it, the state had a monopoly on airlines as well.

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:53.360
[Amit Varma]: All we had then was Air India and Indian Airlines.

00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:57.880
[Amit Varma]: Airlines were prohibitively expensive for most people, including us.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:02.160
[Amit Varma]: That changed in the 1990s, when India was forced to liberalize because of the balance

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:04.960
[Amit Varma]: of payments crisis of 1991.

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:09.160
[Amit Varma]: Telecoms and airlines were thrown open to private players, whose incentives were different

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:10.280
[Amit Varma]: from the government.

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:14.320
[Amit Varma]: The government survives because it has a monopoly on violence.

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:19.440
[Amit Varma]: When it needs more money, it simply takes it from us the people, the bakras, its subjects,

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:21.120
[Amit Varma]: by force.

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:24.720
[Amit Varma]: Private players in a free market, when they are not cronies of the government, have only

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:26.160
[Amit Varma]: one way to survive.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:28.820
[Amit Varma]: They need to provide value to their customers.

00:02:28.820 --> 00:02:33.120
[Amit Varma]: The freer the markets, the more the competition, the harder they have to try.

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:36.280
[Amit Varma]: And relatively free markets transform telecom and airlines.

00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:39.380
[Amit Varma]: Today if you want a phone, you don't have to wait for five years.

00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:44.600
[Amit Varma]: You can get it in five minutes at a very low price, without having to bribe anyone.

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:49.960
[Amit Varma]: Equally, air travel is affordable for vastly more people than it used to be.

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:54.880
[Amit Varma]: Now all this is very nice, but useful as telephones and airlines are, there is one thing that

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:59.720
[Amit Varma]: is far more important for us, and for our nation, education.

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:03.920
[Amit Varma]: The government has done a terrible job of providing education to its people for over

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:05.700
[Amit Varma]: 70 years.

00:03:05.700 --> 00:03:10.400
[Amit Varma]: As bad as it used to do in telecoms and airlines before those markets were opened up.

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:15.240
[Amit Varma]: And yet, there are enormous restraints on private players in the marketplace, especially

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:20.560
[Amit Varma]: those who provide budget education to the poor, which, contrary to popular stereotype,

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:23.080
[Amit Varma]: is a majority of private schools.

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:27.080
[Amit Varma]: In less important fields like telecom and airlines, the government has allowed society

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:30.960
[Amit Varma]: to help itself, which is basically what markets do.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:35.680
[Amit Varma]: But not in the case of education, and our children still suffer for this.

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:36.680
[Amit Varma]: This is a crime.

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:41.680
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:45.800
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science.

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:49.840
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bhadma.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:51.560
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:54.920
[Amit Varma]: Today's episode is about education in India.

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:57.200
[Amit Varma]: And my guest is my friend Amit Chandra.

00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:00.840
[Amit Varma]: Amit has been a researcher and activist in the field of education since the early days

00:04:00.840 --> 00:04:06.520
[Amit Varma]: of the century, working first for the Center for Civil Society, and now with NISA, or the

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:09.360
[Amit Varma]: National Independent Schools Alliance.

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:11.200
[Amit Varma]: He has strong thoughts on education.

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:15.440
[Amit Varma]: He terms it a fraud committed on the people of India by the government.

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:19.840
[Amit Varma]: In this episode, we decided not to talk about the many solutions people offer, like school

00:04:19.840 --> 00:04:25.920
[Amit Varma]: vouchers and so on, but just describe the scope of this fraud, which, in our opinion,

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:30.960
[Amit Varma]: is actually inevitable because of the way the incentives of government are structured.

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:35.480
[Amit Varma]: I've done episodes on education before, you can find them on seen and seen.in, but this

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:39.800
[Amit Varma]: was the longest and most comprehensive one so far, so do listen in.

00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:43.480
[Amit Varma]: But first, before that, a quick commercial break.

