[Amit Varma]: So download the IVM podcast app today.

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Amit, welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:38.840
[Amit Varma]: Amit, all of us know, I mean, all Indians know that we have a problem with education.

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:44.720
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, that problem is not just restricted to like the education sector and

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:46.640
[Amit Varma]: children studying and so on and so forth.

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:51.760
[Amit Varma]: It cuts across every level of society, even the unemployment problem that we have in India

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:58.440
[Amit Varma]: today, to some extent is because our education isn't skilling people enough, and you see

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:03.160
[Amit Varma]: so many people come out of the education system and actually not be good for anything.

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:06.920
[Amit Varma]: And I know that you have worked in this field for more than a decade and a half and you

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:12.800
[Amit Varma]: have very deep and strongly felt feelings about what is happening in education in this

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:13.800
[Amit Varma]: country.

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:15.720
[Amit Varma]: You've often described it as a fraud.

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:23.020
[Amit Varma]: So I'd like you today to elaborate on different aspects of our education system and the politics

00:06:23.020 --> 00:06:24.720
[Amit Varma]: behind it.

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:28.720
[Amit Varma]: What is been your biggest learning in all these years?

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:31.240
[Guest]: Thank you so much for having me on your show.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:41.040
[Guest]: Yeah, so one insight after working for so such a long year in education sector, I realized

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:47.680
[Guest]: that something that we are not doing right to our next generation and somehow for whatever

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:52.040
[Guest]: reason, reasons we can explore later.

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:57.000
[Guest]: But what we are doing, it won't be wrong if we simply call it that we are frauding our

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:58.000
[Guest]: next generation.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:04.760
[Guest]: And we, our system is frauding our own children.

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:11.080
[Guest]: One simple way to give you why I'm saying and why I have such a strong opinion is, you

00:07:11.080 --> 00:07:17.040
[Guest]: would know recently by the government, there were advertisements for government jobs and

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:21.780
[Guest]: those were of peons and chaprasis and all of that kind.

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:29.800
[Guest]: And you know that for thousand position, you get applications of millions, which would

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:37.440
[Guest]: also include applications by those who have done MBA, LLB, even PhD, they're applying

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:39.560
[Guest]: for a job of peon.

00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:40.560
[Guest]: Why?

00:07:40.560 --> 00:07:46.800
[Guest]: It simply means the certificate that they are holding, it might say that you are a B-take,

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:51.760
[Guest]: you are engineering graduate, but they don't have that skill, neither they think that they

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:58.760
[Guest]: are able to, they have those skills to claim themselves as their rightful position of engineers,

00:07:58.760 --> 00:07:59.760
[Guest]: right?

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:06.000
[Guest]: So that simply gives you an indication that this entire system, which has designed and

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:11.000
[Guest]: which you have not a fake certificate, it's an original certificate, while there have

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:16.080
[Guest]: been several debates about people with fake certificates, also, this is original certificate,

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:21.160
[Guest]: but it has completely artificial value, it has no real value.

00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:26.920
[Guest]: And therefore, I say we are cheating our own students, we are cheating our people.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:31.360
[Amit Varma]: And this is what, you know, activists like you called degree inflation, that you have

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:34.880
[Amit Varma]: an inflation in degrees and these degrees are meaningless.

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:39.720
[Amit Varma]: And these degrees, of course, are degrees which the ones you mentioned, LLB, MBA, they

00:08:39.720 --> 00:08:41.640
[Amit Varma]: come at a much later stage.

00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:47.860
[Amit Varma]: But according to you, the fraud starts right from the earliest stage of schooling, because,

00:08:47.860 --> 00:08:53.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, surveys like the famous ACER reports, and so on, listeners should search for these

00:08:53.160 --> 00:09:00.320
[Amit Varma]: ACER reports on Google, A-S-E-R, and they show learning outcomes across the country.

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:01.320
[Amit Varma]: And they are mind blowing.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:05.880
[Amit Varma]: They talk about how people in 10th standard can't add or subtract or, you know, put a

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:12.200
[Amit Varma]: sentence together and they are in just, you know, and even by forget come out with a degree

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:17.120
[Amit Varma]: later on, even before they get to that stage, they are unequipped for anything.

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:18.960
[Guest]: What has gone wrong?

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:19.960
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:26.520
[Guest]: And at times, I think why there is no human cry about either ACER report or similar government

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:27.520
[Guest]: reports also.

00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:36.440
[Guest]: So if you know, when PISA report came in 2010, India was ranked, if I'm correct, 72nd out

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:42.360
[Guest]: of 73 countries only next to Kazakhstan on the learning outcome.

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:47.600
[Guest]: And that to think of what was the most interesting part was the response from the government.

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:54.920
[Guest]: Government decided not to participate in PISA assessment and ranking from next year onwards,

00:09:54.920 --> 00:10:01.920
[Guest]: which is, to me, something shooting the messenger, shooting the messenger, exactly, instead of

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:06.520
[Guest]: taking that as a benchmark and learning and finding out what is wrong.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:14.600
[Guest]: And you say, okay, next round of PISA report, we'll put a benchmark for ourselves and we

00:10:14.600 --> 00:10:19.280
[Guest]: come up with better ranking, something what we are doing now on ease of doing business

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:20.880
[Guest]: index, right.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:28.280
[Guest]: But the response in 2010 was government decided not to participate in it.

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:34.400
[Guest]: And they could also criticize and give certain reasons about methodology and foreign style

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:36.640
[Guest]: of conducting assessments and all.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:40.640
[Guest]: But when ACER did it, ACER also shows pathetic learning outcome.

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:41.640
[Guest]: What is that?

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:49.000
[Guest]: It says 6th grade students, 64% of 6th grade students cannot do basic Hindi, English and

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.240
[Guest]: maths of 2nd grade.

00:10:51.240 --> 00:11:00.720
[Guest]: I mean, 64% of 6th grade students not able to do 2nd grade learning outcome.

00:11:00.720 --> 00:11:01.720
[Guest]: What does it indicate?

00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:06.840
[Guest]: I mean, certainly massively we have failed to deliver what is basics and they also do

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:09.480
[Guest]: a basic assessment.

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:15.320
[Guest]: Even if we are not able to provide that, we should fire ourselves as simple as that.

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:17.100
[Amit Varma]: It's a criminal activity.

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:21.440
[Amit Varma]: And one of the tragic things here is that, you know, we the elites who have the most

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:27.000
[Amit Varma]: volume in media and all of that, and we think, hey, our kids are going to a good school.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:33.480
[Amit Varma]: And we sort of ignore this as not as big a deal as it is, but it just impacts everyone.

00:11:33.480 --> 00:11:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And we're talking about the point you made that if a 6th standard kid cannot show learning

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:41.920
[Amit Varma]: outcomes of 2nd standard, 64% of them.

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:46.120
[Amit Varma]: Also consider what it does as you go down the road, when he reaches a 7th standard,

00:11:46.120 --> 00:11:48.080
[Amit Varma]: can he even understand what is being taught?

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:49.640
[Amit Varma]: He won't be able to cope.

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:55.280
[Amit Varma]: And when he's not able to cope with that learning, it affects your self-confidence, it affects

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:59.440
[Amit Varma]: your morale, it affects your eagerness to learn more and more, it creates a vicious

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:02.920
[Amit Varma]: circle and we just lose generations of children like this.

00:12:02.920 --> 00:12:06.680
[Guest]: Okay, let me tell you something very interesting here as well.

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:11.160
[Guest]: So first thing is certainly we have failed to deliver whatever is even basic desirable

00:12:11.160 --> 00:12:14.240
[Guest]: result we were thinking of.

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:22.840
[Guest]: Now, government had in 2009 passed this act called Right to Education Act, wherein their

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:31.240
[Guest]: idea was that they will have 100% literacy rate and therefore also 100% school enrollment.

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:36.240
[Guest]: Now since the quality is so bad, and if you look into data, I have actually also brought

00:12:36.240 --> 00:12:45.320
[Guest]: this report in case we need to dig data, that students, and you have rightly pointed out,

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:50.800
[Guest]: are migrating, they're abandoning government schools and coming to private schools.

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.840
[Guest]: That's one reason for quality.

00:12:52.840 --> 00:12:57.880
[Guest]: But whatever students they have, they are not able to teach and they have set the goal

00:12:57.880 --> 00:12:59.840
[Guest]: of 100% literacy.

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:05.240
[Guest]: Now then think of what they are doing wrong to meet the goal without teaching.

00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:11.520
[Guest]: And that is how they have beautifully exploited this provision of Right to Education Act called

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:19.320
[Guest]: No Detention Policy, which means up to 8th grade, well certainly there is a fascinating

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:24.920
[Guest]: way of justifying No Detention Policy as well.

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:29.120
[Guest]: Or there could be a sincere logic also, I don't really want to get into it, but how

00:13:29.120 --> 00:13:30.920
[Guest]: that has been used.

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:39.000
[Guest]: Up to 8th standard, then you don't fail at all, which simply means it's a mass certification

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.680
[Guest]: program without any assessment.

00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:46.560
[Guest]: So up to 8th you keep coming to my place, there is nothing and at the end I give you

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:54.280
[Guest]: a degree or a certificate saying you are 8th pass and we achieve as a nation 100% literacy.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:59.320
[Amit Varma]: And because you need to do nothing to get to that 8th pass point, that immediately becomes

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:04.200
[Amit Varma]: meaningless and therefore all the way down the line other certificates also become meaningless

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:07.900
[Amit Varma]: because a certificate has no correlation with the learning.

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:08.900
[Guest]: It has nothing.

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:16.400
[Guest]: And let's say government school students, it has similar kind of impact on private

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:17.800
[Guest]: schools as well.

00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:26.280
[Guest]: So private schools who are being in some sense glamorized or justified in terms of doing

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:33.360
[Guest]: well etc. or students who are growing up or we call millenials who are growing up that

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:39.200
[Guest]: thinking okay the assessment is student centric etc. we have not failed blah blah blah.

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:45.520
[Guest]: But the moment they are going to 10th standard or 12th standard or later, they realize that

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:53.120
[Guest]: they know nothing or almost nothing or they get through a psychological situation where

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:59.680
[Guest]: they are certainly reflecting upon themselves that all along they have been kind of applauded

00:14:59.680 --> 00:15:04.560
[Guest]: for doing what they are doing and later on they realize that possibly what they were

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:11.120
[Guest]: doing was certainly not wrong for almost everything for which they were given 3 stars or 5 stars.

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:17.480
[Guest]: And which later on if they finally get into some kind of let's say medical or engineering

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:23.320
[Guest]: good colleges, you also see that increasing rate of societal where students are actually

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:24.920
[Guest]: not able to cope up.

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:29.800
[Guest]: Now there is family pressure also they have paid some good fee or donation or whatever

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:37.080
[Guest]: and got a seat of let's say medical or engineering in high reputed college and under society

00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:41.760
[Guest]: and parents and peer pressure they know that they got into this good college.

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:47.120
[Guest]: But if they are not able to cope up they don't want to go back to family and say I am a failure

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:52.400
[Guest]: and that is where I believe there is that is also one of the factors leading to increase

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:55.480
[Guest]: societal attempts among students.

00:15:55.480 --> 00:16:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So I mean exactly like this is so basic that a failure in our education leads to a failure

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.180
[Amit Varma]: in every aspect of our society it affects everything.

00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:08.720
[Amit Varma]: It affects our employment situations because as much as the fact that there aren't enough

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:15.440
[Amit Varma]: jobs being generated there is also the fact that we are churning out millions of people

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:19.800
[Amit Varma]: with the degrees that really are meaningless and they are not equipped in the job market.

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:25.920
[Amit Varma]: This affects their confidence and their sense of self worth and it's just a massive social

00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:26.920
[Amit Varma]: problem.

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:31.360
[Amit Varma]: So for a moment you know and I think this is something all my listeners would agree

00:16:31.360 --> 00:16:36.360
[Amit Varma]: on that even if within whatever elite cocoons and I'm assuming that everyone who listens

00:16:36.360 --> 00:16:42.000
[Amit Varma]: to the podcast is elite in some way right like you and me but whatever life may be like

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.960
[Amit Varma]: there in the cocoons I think everybody agrees education in India is badly broken.

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:52.060
[Amit Varma]: Now what I want your sort of insights on and you've been in the field doing all this work

00:16:52.060 --> 00:16:57.440
[Amit Varma]: for 15 years not just at the micro level but at a broader level of fixing policy and trying

00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:04.120
[Amit Varma]: to fix the structure of education in the country take me through some of the root causes for

00:17:04.120 --> 00:17:06.280
[Amit Varma]: this problem.

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:10.440
[Guest]: This is something very difficult to identify one root cause.

00:17:10.440 --> 00:17:15.720
[Amit Varma]: So give me a laundry list whatever comes to mind let's just go with because we have created

00:17:15.720 --> 00:17:22.080
[Guest]: such a mess now even this mess has piled up so big decoding the root of the mess is too

00:17:22.080 --> 00:17:30.880
[Guest]: difficult but one thing certainly I would say is we have highly politicized and bureaucratized

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:35.120
[Guest]: our education system that is certainly not acceptable.

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:40.320
[Guest]: In terms of this you can see some sense of nationalization or controlling the entire

00:17:40.320 --> 00:17:49.760
[Guest]: education system and which is also very discriminatory and one thing also I talk about is it's pretty

00:17:49.760 --> 00:18:01.000
[Guest]: anti-poor while certainly government may claim that almost everything is free if you get

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:08.920
[Guest]: into government schools and you might find that their per child expenditure per year

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:14.840
[Guest]: goes ranges between 30,000 to 60,000 rupees.

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:23.920
[Guest]: So if that is the amount being spent on per child per year then certainly it is a massive

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:29.880
[Guest]: expenditure and that is the price on which you can in some private schools you can find

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:32.640
[Guest]: decent education that's one.

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:42.160
[Guest]: Second thing happens to be that government lets out norms for all kinds of schooling.

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:50.040
[Guest]: I'll give you example if you if let's say you want to start a school in urban area you

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:58.560
[Guest]: need one acre of land if you want CBSE affiliated schools or if it is a rural area around two

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:06.100
[Guest]: acres of land and thereafter the number of classrooms so for each section there should

00:19:06.100 --> 00:19:13.160
[Guest]: be or for each class there should be a separate room, principal's rooms, teacher's room, library,

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:20.680
[Guest]: separate toilets, separate drinking water, laboratory etc etc, playground, size of your

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:27.520
[Guest]: staircases, size of window, fire and safety requirements and everything.

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:34.840
[Guest]: If by this norm if any tier one or tier two city that you want to start a school you would

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:44.360
[Guest]: require an investment today of at least around 50 crores to start one school and that is

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:46.720
[Guest]: only when I'm talking just money.

00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:53.520
[Guest]: It also has a number of licenses and permissions and which on an average goes around 30 licenses

00:19:53.520 --> 00:20:02.080
[Guest]: or permissions altogether and therefore what you see if school is being started at this

00:20:02.080 --> 00:20:08.400
[Guest]: cost at this price and it also gets thousand students enrollment your price point happens

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:16.140
[Guest]: to be very high so simply it doesn't make sense in economic terms and the moment the

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:23.840
[Guest]: price is very high which simply means only elite or few people can afford schooling rest

00:20:23.840 --> 00:20:29.920
[Guest]: are supposed to go to government or municipality schools which certainly are not giving desired

00:20:29.920 --> 00:20:35.080
[Guest]: results and that is what led to private school revolution in India.

00:20:35.080 --> 00:20:40.200
[Amit Varma]: So before I come and I want to talk about this private school revolution in India and

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:46.440
[Amit Varma]: especially the rise of budget private schools and parents of the poorest families voting

00:20:46.440 --> 00:20:50.680
[Amit Varma]: with their feet and taking their kid out of government schools and putting them into budget

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:56.120
[Amit Varma]: private schools which are like operating in holes in the walls and paying for that sums

00:20:56.120 --> 00:20:59.160
[Amit Varma]: of money which will seem trivial to us but means a lot to them.

00:20:59.160 --> 00:21:04.560
[Amit Varma]: But before I come to that I want to address like three broad points that you raised at

00:21:04.560 --> 00:21:10.560
[Amit Varma]: the start of your answer where you spoke about politicization of education, bureaucratization

00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:16.200
[Amit Varma]: of education and first I want to address a great point you made about the sort of the

00:21:16.200 --> 00:21:22.200
[Amit Varma]: attitude of nationalization of education where you have a sort of a command and control way

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:24.000
[Amit Varma]: of looking at it.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:30.120
[Amit Varma]: So let me sort of try to paraphrase what that might be and you tell me if you agree with

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:34.840
[Amit Varma]: the assessment and what you can add to that is that in education what we have tended to

00:21:34.840 --> 00:21:40.800
[Amit Varma]: do is that like in all parts of our economy after independence we decided that we need

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:44.320
[Amit Varma]: a command and control structure and especially because it is so important the government

00:21:44.320 --> 00:21:50.040
[Amit Varma]: needs to make sure that education is provided to the people and one of the things they did

00:21:50.040 --> 00:21:54.040
[Amit Varma]: was not just pour money into education and government schools and all which is great,

00:21:54.040 --> 00:21:58.200
[Amit Varma]: but they also stopped the private sector from coming up, they placed restrictions like you

00:21:58.200 --> 00:22:02.960
[Amit Varma]: cannot open a school for profit which came out of a mistaken notion that profit is a

00:22:02.960 --> 00:22:08.680
[Amit Varma]: bad thing necessarily while you can really only get profit by benefiting society.

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:12.400
[Amit Varma]: And I've had an episode on this a long time back which listeners can find at seen unseen

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:18.320
[Amit Varma]: radhai and the profit motive in education with Parth Shah and the result of that was

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:22.360
[Amit Varma]: that while there was this demand for quality education, the supply wasn't allowed.

00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:28.080
[Amit Varma]: The government said no, we will do the supply and there were too many restrictions on private

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:29.080
[Amit Varma]: schools.

00:22:29.080 --> 00:22:33.280
[Amit Varma]: So there's a profit motive around which people find ways like you have trusts and all that,

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:36.880
[Amit Varma]: but you have to find jogar ways around it and the other is a kind of regulations you

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:40.920
[Amit Varma]: pointed out that your playground has to be this size, you need to have so many toilets,

00:22:40.920 --> 00:22:45.560
[Amit Varma]: you need to have falana dhimkana rather than leave it to the market and leave it to parents

00:22:45.560 --> 00:22:49.080
[Amit Varma]: to decide what kind of school they want to send their kid to, they restrict the supply

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:54.280
[Amit Varma]: so badly that there is a massive shortfall there, which the government itself because

00:22:54.280 --> 00:22:57.360
[Amit Varma]: of incentives can't really provide.

00:22:57.360 --> 00:23:00.440
[Amit Varma]: So structurally firstly, have I summarized it correctly?

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:05.480
[Guest]: Pretty much, pretty much, in fact something that you were talking about and the norms

00:23:05.480 --> 00:23:16.040
[Guest]: I talked about is, before 2009, before Right to Education Act, unrecognized schools also

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:23.680
[Guest]: could operate and there was number of unrecognized schools which are giving only primary education,

00:23:23.680 --> 00:23:30.120
[Guest]: they could operate but RT Act has made it mandatory to be recognized and actually what

00:23:30.120 --> 00:23:37.560
[Guest]: that has led to, post this act around 20,000 schools have already closed down, so 20,000

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:42.840
[Guest]: low-cost private schools which came up as an alternative, as what you talked about parents

00:23:42.840 --> 00:23:50.160
[Guest]: are choosing by feet and they are also paying money because they think that education is

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:55.680
[Guest]: their only hope, if you want to change whatever poor people have gone through and they want

00:23:55.680 --> 00:24:02.360
[Guest]: to change their fortune, finally is for the next generation through education, otherwise

00:24:02.360 --> 00:24:08.600
[Guest]: they know that they don't have a huge investment to set up a business or something like that

00:24:08.600 --> 00:24:14.160
[Guest]: and that is also being closed down and therefore that leads to this major question and that's

00:24:14.160 --> 00:24:20.480
[Guest]: why I really want to very strongly say everything is fraud in education, that we are certainly

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:26.200
[Guest]: cheating our next generation and if then we are thinking of something like Make in India

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:34.200
[Guest]: or Start of India etc etc, it's all just shame, I mean we can't do basics, while I talked

00:24:34.200 --> 00:24:39.080
[Guest]: about politicization, you also have to think about why all of these things have sustained

00:24:39.080 --> 00:24:46.240
[Guest]: for so long, how come we were able to control, while talking about education any bureaucrat

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:52.120
[Guest]: would give you a reply that education is a state subject, so there is nothing called

00:24:52.120 --> 00:25:00.640
[Guest]: nationalization etc, but directly or indirectly it's all controlled by governments, certainly

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:07.080
[Guest]: they have certain liberty to pick up which language to use etc etc, but by and large

00:25:07.080 --> 00:25:12.520
[Guest]: they follow NCRT curriculum and there is a similar trend, so what let's say Gujarat adopts

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:19.280
[Guest]: also Maharashtra adopts and then Karnataka adopts etc and it spreads out, when I also

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:27.200
[Guest]: talked about politicization of education, specifically you should look for politicians

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:37.040
[Guest]: who are either coming from education background or are highly influenced by people in education,

00:25:37.040 --> 00:25:45.080
[Guest]: so something like that has happened is union of government school teachers, something I

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:50.280
[Guest]: specifically point out and the kind of role that they play in education policy or its

00:25:50.280 --> 00:25:58.600
[Guest]: execution is, we know that there is no accountability, I mean one of the reason why it happens to

00:25:58.600 --> 00:26:05.600
[Guest]: be a very lucrative occupation is, this is the only job where you are, the school operates

00:26:05.600 --> 00:26:13.120
[Guest]: for 210 days or something around it, it's largely their day or in case there are second

00:26:13.120 --> 00:26:22.560
[Guest]: shifts it's a 4 to 6 hours job, with as number of holidays and decent pay per week.

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:26.960
[Amit Varma]: And despite that there are huge rates of absenteeism in government schools.

00:26:26.960 --> 00:26:33.920
[Guest]: There was a report by World Bank which says on any day around 25% of teachers are absent,

00:26:33.920 --> 00:26:41.240
[Guest]: which means one-fourth, randomly and those who are there, they are not motivated or you

00:26:41.240 --> 00:26:46.280
[Guest]: can also look into who all are going into this government teaching occupation.

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:50.900
[Guest]: Those who are looking to become a great teacher, certainly not, all those what they are looking

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:57.480
[Guest]: for a one state job, a government safe secure job, their motivation is certainly not teaching,

00:26:57.480 --> 00:27:02.000
[Guest]: however I'm not kind of vilifying all of those young talent which is getting into.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:07.480
[Amit Varma]: It's a structural issue, it's not like individuals are at fault, those teachers are at fault,

00:27:07.480 --> 00:27:09.800
[Amit Varma]: they are in a sense also victims.

00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:16.400
[Guest]: Right, they are also victims and that is also good, I have actually a friend who got into

00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:26.400
[Guest]: government job as a school teacher and she had to pay bribe to just claim her salary.

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:35.520
[Guest]: Anyways, so the other role I wanted to point was the role of teacher union.

00:27:35.520 --> 00:27:42.720
[Guest]: Also because teacher happens to be an influential personality in any community, which has been

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:46.800
[Guest]: so good, I mean we have been proud of that.

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:54.280
[Guest]: But since they are influential, no political representative actually want to get into anything

00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:59.360
[Guest]: which causes conflict or confrontation, right.

00:27:59.360 --> 00:28:06.080
[Guest]: Also if you get into a little further more detail, when voting happens and polling happens,

00:28:06.080 --> 00:28:11.680
[Guest]: the only person present inside the polling booth is a teacher because all of these teachers

00:28:11.680 --> 00:28:14.160
[Guest]: have polling duty.

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:20.360
[Guest]: And you know inside they can either influence the voters or do any mess thing which you

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:27.120
[Guest]: don't really want to get into and therefore they are able to influence political parties

00:28:27.120 --> 00:28:33.880
[Guest]: who come or go in government and therefore they are able to control it.

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:38.800
[Guest]: And that is one of the reasons why you find in Right to Education Act all kind of norms

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:45.760
[Guest]: in terms of input or school recognition, salary, qualification, but not as much in terms of

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:52.280
[Guest]: duty and if duty is not being performed, accountability or penalty or punishment or whatever you could

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:53.560
[Guest]: think of.

00:28:53.560 --> 00:28:55.160
[Guest]: That's completely not there.

00:28:55.160 --> 00:29:04.320
[Guest]: And therefore, so what happens is it's politicized, the entire management of education, management

00:29:04.320 --> 00:29:10.040
[Guest]: in government schools is not done by management professionals.

00:29:10.040 --> 00:29:12.120
[Guest]: It's all done by bureaucrats.

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:16.280
[Guest]: So those will be block education officers or district education officers or education

00:29:16.280 --> 00:29:19.600
[Guest]: secretary or additional secretaries.

00:29:19.600 --> 00:29:27.720
[Guest]: They all completely behave like inspectors who are coming here to inspect, penalize and

00:29:27.720 --> 00:29:32.400
[Guest]: in the process also make money for themselves, frankly speaking, and that happens to be the

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:33.400
[Guest]: only aim.

00:29:33.400 --> 00:29:39.280
[Guest]: Nowhere, I will tell you one incident, I was in a school in Trichy, I was visiting and

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:45.040
[Guest]: I was interacting with the school leaders and they said their experience.

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:53.280
[Guest]: One of the guy told me that 10-20 years ago, when education officers used to visit schools,

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:59.920
[Guest]: we used to prepare students, ki wo aayega, ye puchega, ye bolega, to kaise jawab doge,

00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:03.720
[Guest]: kya karoge, kaise khade hona hai, etc, etc.

00:30:03.720 --> 00:30:09.120
[Guest]: Now when the education officer comes to visit school, we prepare the building.

00:30:09.120 --> 00:30:13.760
[Guest]: So that the toilet is fixed, there is drinking water, it's in clean, it's painted, the benches

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:20.720
[Guest]: are there, those sprinklers are there or fire safety equipment is there.

00:30:20.720 --> 00:30:26.640
[Guest]: So all of that focus has completely shifted on input rather than quality of education

00:30:26.640 --> 00:30:33.060
[Guest]: and output and which I don't see improving as long as the bureaucrats leading it.

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:37.640
[Guest]: There has to be some kind of educationist coming in the role and they deciding or at

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:43.000
[Guest]: least working together with schools, figuring out what is wrong happening.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:47.180
[Amit Varma]: So I want to examine, I want to go a little further into this point and examine the interplay

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:50.360
[Amit Varma]: between power, accountability and incentives.

