[Amit Varma]: In this episode, we are discussing the state of education in India.

00:31:53.360 --> 00:31:59.080
[Amit Varma]: And my guest is Amit Chandra, who's been a researcher and activist in this area for more

00:31:59.080 --> 00:32:02.560
[Amit Varma]: than a decade and a half and has very deep insights about it.

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:07.240
[Amit Varma]: And before the break, Amit, you were talking about how teachers unions are so strong and

00:32:07.240 --> 00:32:11.120
[Amit Varma]: they're a very powerful interest group, and therefore they control a lot of the politics

00:32:11.120 --> 00:32:12.120
[Amit Varma]: of it.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:17.760
[Amit Varma]: Now, tell me if my understanding is correct, because I kind of try to look everything through

00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:20.720
[Amit Varma]: the economic lens of what are the incentives.

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:25.880
[Guest]: And before we get into, because then we are going to the next step of discussion, let

00:32:25.880 --> 00:32:31.080
[Guest]: me give you one more example, which tells you when I say fraud at several levels of

00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:35.200
[Guest]: fraud, not only with the kids, with the system, with the teacher, with the quality, almost

00:32:35.200 --> 00:32:36.200
[Guest]: everything.

00:32:36.200 --> 00:32:37.200
[Guest]: Go ahead.

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:47.440
[Guest]: Very recently, CAG, which is the auditing body, came up with its report, and it estimated

00:32:47.440 --> 00:32:56.040
[Guest]: 1.1 crore fake student enrollment in government schools of Uttar Pradesh alone.

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:57.520
[Guest]: That's more than 10 million people.

00:32:57.520 --> 00:32:58.520
[Guest]: Wow.

00:32:58.520 --> 00:32:59.520
[Guest]: Yes.

00:32:59.520 --> 00:33:00.520
[Guest]: Fake enrollment.

00:33:00.520 --> 00:33:01.520
[Guest]: Fake student enrollment.

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:03.800
[Guest]: Now, you would wonder why there are fake student enrollment.

00:33:03.800 --> 00:33:04.800
[Guest]: Right.

00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:09.040
[Guest]: Yes, because that decides the amount of fund you would get.

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:10.960
[Guest]: You know, there is a midday meal scheme.

00:33:10.960 --> 00:33:11.960
[Guest]: Right.

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:18.560
[Guest]: So, assume the cost per child per day is 10 rupees, right?

00:33:18.560 --> 00:33:19.560
[Guest]: What does it mean?

00:33:19.560 --> 00:33:25.680
[Amit Varma]: 10 crore rupees every day is 100 crore per day expenditure on midday meals.

00:33:25.680 --> 00:33:26.680
[Guest]: Yes.

00:33:26.680 --> 00:33:28.480
[Guest]: Which is going into someone's pocket.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:29.480
[Guest]: Right.

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:35.960
[Guest]: Then there are altogether 14 kind of freebies, which is given shoes, socks, uniform, textbooks,

00:33:35.960 --> 00:33:36.960
[Guest]: etc.

00:33:36.960 --> 00:33:39.880
[Guest]: Stationery, all of those.

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:48.240
[Guest]: Then the teacher positions are created and all this transfer posting appointment happens

00:33:48.240 --> 00:33:50.840
[Guest]: on the basis of number of students there.

00:33:50.840 --> 00:33:51.840
[Guest]: Right.

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:57.520
[Guest]: And also you want to increase your enrollment and you show you are performing better.

00:33:57.520 --> 00:33:58.520
[Guest]: Right.

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:03.120
[Guest]: There is also now, at least with ASER and government data, even MHRD is conducting,

00:34:03.120 --> 00:34:05.440
[Guest]: there is NAS.

00:34:05.440 --> 00:34:10.440
[Guest]: So now the data is being collected that whether students are enrolled or not coming or not.

00:34:10.440 --> 00:34:16.360
[Guest]: So you are fuzzing all the data to show that students are there and they are coming.

00:34:16.360 --> 00:34:20.280
[Guest]: However, they are not present in school.

00:34:20.280 --> 00:34:26.720
[Guest]: They are not learning all the money is being eaten or drunken by others.

00:34:26.720 --> 00:34:29.400
[Amit Varma]: With all the different freebies and so on.

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:30.400
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:34:30.400 --> 00:34:35.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is such an amazing illustration of how government inevitably tends to descend

00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:40.560
[Amit Varma]: into a parasitic role and everything in India, especially just becomes a jhol.

00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:45.880
[Amit Varma]: But to get back to the question of incentives, which I think is worth unpacking for our listeners,

00:34:45.880 --> 00:34:52.040
[Amit Varma]: is that because teachers in government schools essentially have power without accountability

00:34:52.040 --> 00:34:56.400
[Amit Varma]: because they are teachers, they are tenured, they get the salary they get, but they are

00:34:56.400 --> 00:35:01.560
[Amit Varma]: not actually held accountable in terms of the kind of education they provide.

00:35:01.560 --> 00:35:04.400
[Amit Varma]: And very often there are more teachers than you need because if there are so many fake

00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:08.920
[Amit Varma]: students and you have to maintain a student teacher ratio that rationalizes the appointment

00:35:08.920 --> 00:35:13.320
[Amit Varma]: of many more teachers who are not required and who probably won't show up to work.

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:16.880
[Amit Varma]: And because the incentives are so flawed, because they don't actually need to deliver,

00:35:16.880 --> 00:35:20.040
[Amit Varma]: unlike a private school, which is dependent on the fees coming in every month.

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:22.520
[Amit Varma]: So there's pressure to actually perform and compete.

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:28.320
[Amit Varma]: But because that pressure isn't here and the incentives are so bad, your learning outcomes

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:33.360
[Amit Varma]: are bad on a per capita basis, in the sense, I don't know whether it was you, but I heard

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:41.000
[Amit Varma]: this statistic recently about how the same outcomes are provided by private schools for

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:46.080
[Amit Varma]: one third the cost of a government school, the per student cost, despite the fact that

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:47.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, governments.

00:35:47.480 --> 00:35:53.960
[Guest]: This study, this paper was done by Karthik Muralidharan in Hyderabad schools, wherein

00:35:53.960 --> 00:36:01.920
[Guest]: he simply compared students of government schools and students of low cost private school,

00:36:01.920 --> 00:36:06.120
[Guest]: not just private schools, very low cost with the similar kind of economic background of

00:36:06.120 --> 00:36:08.420
[Guest]: students.

00:36:08.420 --> 00:36:16.680
[Guest]: And he found that while the learning outcome in those low cost private school was slightly

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:17.960
[Guest]: better.

00:36:17.960 --> 00:36:24.400
[Guest]: So if you are comparing in terms of learning outcome, it's not great, slightly better.

00:36:24.400 --> 00:36:28.520
[Guest]: But in terms of cost, those happens to be one third.

00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:33.320
[Guest]: So one third of the same cost you can provide in low cost private school, something similar

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:34.320
[Guest]: quality education.

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:40.080
[Amit Varma]: So even if you're not providing a better education in an absolute sense, you are providing much

00:36:40.080 --> 00:36:44.280
[Amit Varma]: more bang for the buck, which really matters for poor people.

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:49.720
[Amit Varma]: The reason you're doing and again, you know, it's often an unfair sort of rap, which is

00:36:49.720 --> 00:36:53.360
[Amit Varma]: placed on libertarians like me that you think all government is bad and all private is good

00:36:53.360 --> 00:36:54.360
[Amit Varma]: and blah, blah, blah.

00:36:54.360 --> 00:36:55.360
[Amit Varma]: And that's not the case at all.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:58.160
[Amit Varma]: I just come at it from a point of view of incentives.

00:36:58.160 --> 00:37:02.640
[Amit Varma]: And in the case of education, who do you want to be in a position of power?

00:37:02.640 --> 00:37:06.880
[Amit Varma]: You want the children and the parents of those children to be to be the people who have the

00:37:06.880 --> 00:37:09.100
[Amit Varma]: power and who dictate the outcomes.

00:37:09.100 --> 00:37:13.520
[Amit Varma]: And you want teachers to be accountable in terms of the education that they provide.

00:37:13.520 --> 00:37:17.880
[Amit Varma]: And you have those incentives in private schools, including low cost private schools, where

00:37:17.880 --> 00:37:21.600
[Amit Varma]: the parents will just walk with their feet and go elsewhere if they feel the education

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:23.040
[Amit Varma]: isn't good enough.

00:37:23.040 --> 00:37:29.520
[Amit Varma]: But in a government school set up the way our school system is set up, that power is,

00:37:29.520 --> 00:37:33.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, the kids and their parents aren't empowered with that, because teachers are

00:37:33.880 --> 00:37:35.760
[Amit Varma]: completely unaccountable.

00:37:35.760 --> 00:37:41.400
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, whenever any reform is proposed, the teachers will obviously oppose that reform,

00:37:41.400 --> 00:37:47.120
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, this brings accountability, that brings accountability, the system works

00:37:47.120 --> 00:37:49.920
[Amit Varma]: so beautifully for them, why would they mess with it?

00:37:49.920 --> 00:37:55.600
[Guest]: While we talked about this study by Karthik Muralidharan, let me also mention, and your

00:37:55.600 --> 00:38:00.840
[Guest]: audience could find out a paper done by Professor Geeta Gandhikindan.

00:38:00.840 --> 00:38:08.520
[Guest]: So what she did, she took all the learning outcome and kind of converted into units.

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:15.680
[Guest]: So units of learning, and compared with the cost, I don't remember exactly, but it comes

00:38:15.680 --> 00:38:24.280
[Guest]: somewhere around, if I'm not mistaken, is that for each unit of learning outcome, if

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:29.720
[Guest]: you compare with government and private school, government schools spend 10 times more, so

00:38:29.720 --> 00:38:34.520
[Guest]: it doesn't give you bang for the buck.

00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:39.320
[Guest]: And the simple reason is, anywhere you go, private sector has efficiency, and that is

00:38:39.320 --> 00:38:41.840
[Guest]: what they are known for.

00:38:41.840 --> 00:38:48.220
[Guest]: And that actually leads to the, in case of accountability and designing system-wise,

00:38:48.220 --> 00:38:54.520
[Guest]: you don't want even centrally designed or at a state level also, which also happens

00:38:54.520 --> 00:39:00.680
[Guest]: to be like a centre, when we have states like UP, which is bigger than several countries,

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:08.360
[Guest]: why can't we trust parents, teachers, or people who are locally, or even students?

00:39:08.360 --> 00:39:17.320
[Guest]: I mean, simply we ask students, at times we have wondered, if students had voting rights,

00:39:17.320 --> 00:39:24.240
[Guest]: the scene today could have been different, because as we talked about politicians trying

00:39:24.240 --> 00:39:28.880
[Guest]: not to take panga with teacher unions, the moment they would realize, okay, now students

00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:30.920
[Guest]: have got voice and voting right.

00:39:30.920 --> 00:39:35.760
[Guest]: And they would certainly force them to think about, could we think of a student-centric

00:39:35.760 --> 00:39:38.480
[Guest]: education model, right?

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:39.960
[Guest]: So why can't we involve them?

00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:42.400
[Guest]: Why can't we simply give them liberty?

00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:51.720
[Guest]: And in case of India, it is common sense, before India becoming democratic, at least

00:39:51.720 --> 00:40:01.680
[Guest]: electoral democratic, education in some sense, and even when Britishers came and introduced

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:04.600
[Guest]: formal education, it was almost free.

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:10.080
[Guest]: And there was no government and therefore there was no politicization or bureaucratization

00:40:10.080 --> 00:40:11.480
[Guest]: of education.

00:40:11.480 --> 00:40:20.840
[Guest]: So we have had history and in fact, if you get into the reports of James Tooley, he says,

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:29.200
[Guest]: in the British India, Bengal province alone had around five lakh schools.

00:40:29.200 --> 00:40:35.680
[Guest]: And today, after like hundreds of years, today, altogether, we have around five lakh schools.

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:42.520
[Guest]: So in that sense, the number of schools that you could kind of compare only Bengal as a

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:48.000
[Guest]: state and currently entire India, and in those sense, the number of schools should have gone

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:52.880
[Guest]: up rather than going down or staying stable, while the population has gone at least 10

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:53.880
[Amit Varma]: times, no?

00:40:53.880 --> 00:40:54.880
[Amit Varma]: Much more than that.

00:40:54.880 --> 00:40:59.120
[Amit Varma]: And because the demand for quality education is always high, I mean, that's what parents

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:03.800
[Amit Varma]: really want a good education for their kids and but that the supply is not allowed to

00:41:03.800 --> 00:41:09.800
[Amit Varma]: exist and the government system has essentially become parasitic, rather than, you know, actually

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:11.460
[Amit Varma]: trying to deliver outcomes.

00:41:11.460 --> 00:41:15.240
[Amit Varma]: But the other point I want to address, and I'm sure you face this all, you know, you

00:41:15.240 --> 00:41:21.440
[Amit Varma]: face this throughout your, the many years you've spent in this, is that when you talk

00:41:21.440 --> 00:41:25.200
[Amit Varma]: of private schools, people often say, oh, private school to manga and you know, government

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:28.600
[Amit Varma]: schools are doing this social service and private schools are too expensive.

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:31.120
[Amit Varma]: But actually, that is a massive myth.

00:41:31.120 --> 00:41:34.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, as James Tooley himself pointed out, for example, in a beautiful book he wrote

00:41:34.720 --> 00:41:39.240
[Amit Varma]: on the subject, all the papers and books that Amit is mentioning, by the way, will be linked

00:41:39.240 --> 00:41:42.200
[Amit Varma]: at the bottom of the page of this podcast.

00:41:42.200 --> 00:41:44.320
[Amit Varma]: So do look for those.

00:41:44.320 --> 00:41:48.440
[Amit Varma]: But to come back to the question, I mean, is it true that private schools are only for

00:41:48.440 --> 00:41:49.440
[Amit Varma]: the rich?

00:41:49.440 --> 00:41:52.240
[Guest]: Not at all, certainly not at all.

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:56.800
[Guest]: And therefore, I have brought this report also, this is called a report on budget private

00:41:56.800 --> 00:41:59.560
[Guest]: schools in India.

00:41:59.560 --> 00:42:06.240
[Guest]: And that is what, therefore, if you look into how schooling has developed in India, you'll

00:42:06.240 --> 00:42:16.720
[Guest]: find at, let's, if we start from independence, country decided to go for a kind of state

00:42:16.720 --> 00:42:19.440
[Guest]: taking responsibility of providing education.

00:42:19.440 --> 00:42:22.880
[Guest]: However, they did not have capacity as much.

00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:29.200
[Guest]: But thereafter started this idea of government schools and private schools.

00:42:29.200 --> 00:42:34.560
[Guest]: But at that point of time, private schools were only for elite or some missionary schools

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:42.520
[Guest]: which were private, with the idea of also spreading religion or as they are called missionary

00:42:42.520 --> 00:42:43.520
[Guest]: schools.

00:42:43.520 --> 00:42:50.200
[Guest]: Similarly, not missionaries in terms of Christian itself, but also other religion.

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:56.720
[Guest]: But slowly as state realized that they don't have capacity, and in fact, if you go back

00:42:56.720 --> 00:43:03.600
[Guest]: to the debates of drafting constitution, at that point of time, there was debate of having

00:43:03.600 --> 00:43:09.720
[Guest]: something called right to education as a fundamental right, so that it's state's responsibility.

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:17.000
[Guest]: But the constitution makers, at least they realized that it's a new nation coming up,

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.320
[Guest]: and state doesn't have that capacity.

00:43:19.320 --> 00:43:27.080
[Guest]: And therefore, they dropped the idea of keeping right to education as a fundamental right.

00:43:27.080 --> 00:43:31.160
[Guest]: So by and large, coming to the point that there has been government schools and small

00:43:31.160 --> 00:43:34.680
[Guest]: private schools and some missionary schools.

00:43:34.680 --> 00:43:39.080
[Guest]: And thereafter, when government realized that there is a capacity issue, they started something

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:44.480
[Guest]: called aided private schools, which means it's a privately run school.

00:43:44.480 --> 00:43:48.160
[Guest]: And if they are able to sustain it for more than three years, then government will pitch

00:43:48.160 --> 00:43:54.120
[Guest]: in with funds, etc., which later on, because then government was funding it, they started

00:43:54.120 --> 00:43:59.600
[Guest]: controlling it, it also become exactly like any government school.

00:43:59.600 --> 00:44:04.800
[Guest]: And this third segment, which is private school, and if you read all of these education policies

00:44:04.800 --> 00:44:11.480
[Guest]: with the national education policy of 1968 or 86 or 92, or the new one we were drafting

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:21.200
[Guest]: or State Education Act, you'll find it takes the view of government schooling.

00:44:21.200 --> 00:44:26.360
[Guest]: So schooling through government institution or aided government institution, there will

00:44:26.360 --> 00:44:32.040
[Guest]: be only a small segment which will say, if there are private school, what are the rules

00:44:32.040 --> 00:44:33.920
[Guest]: and norms, etc.

00:44:33.920 --> 00:44:36.840
[Guest]: And in that sense, it happens to be completely biased.

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:40.800
[Guest]: So you think of government schools, they are ours, we will run them.

00:44:40.800 --> 00:44:46.720
[Guest]: But if it is a private school, then it has norms, guidelines or control mechanism.

00:44:46.720 --> 00:44:51.400
[Guest]: So by approach itself, we are completely biased.

00:44:51.400 --> 00:44:56.720
[Guest]: So government school is ours, we will run it, there is no set timeline, standard, or

00:44:56.720 --> 00:45:00.800
[Guest]: if you have not delivered, what will be the penal mechanism, etc.

00:45:00.800 --> 00:45:03.480
[Guest]: The approach that you take for private schools.

00:45:03.480 --> 00:45:09.800
[Guest]: Anyway, so the main point I want to come to, that this low cost schools or budget private

00:45:09.800 --> 00:45:17.480
[Guest]: schools, the revolution kind of that James Tooley talks about, I don't attribute it as

00:45:17.480 --> 00:45:19.680
[Guest]: a success of policy.

00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:26.680
[Guest]: What I say is, there is a revolution of low cost private school, because the policy provisions

00:45:26.680 --> 00:45:27.680
[Guest]: failed.

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:32.320
[Guest]: Because as a policy issue, we never wanted private schools to flourish.

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:39.520
[Guest]: And therefore, now as government has challenged, and if you look at now the DICE data, almost

00:45:39.520 --> 00:45:46.240
[Guest]: around 40% students are enrolled in private schools, now only around 60%.

00:45:46.240 --> 00:45:54.480
[Guest]: And this I'm saying as a nationwide, you can also find some urban areas, specifically let's

00:45:54.480 --> 00:46:03.720
[Guest]: say Hyderabad, Delhi or Mumbai, where majority of students you'll find going to private schools.

00:46:03.720 --> 00:46:12.720
[Guest]: So the point I wanted to make is, this revolution has as a failure to policy design, neither

00:46:12.720 --> 00:46:16.320
[Guest]: that policy was designed to promote it.

00:46:16.320 --> 00:46:23.480
[Guest]: The other part to answer your question is, whether these are for only elite or rich people?

00:46:23.480 --> 00:46:24.480
[Guest]: Certainly not.

00:46:24.480 --> 00:46:30.440
[Guest]: Once again, I would refer to Professor Geeta Gandhi Kingdon's report, which is in the same

00:46:30.440 --> 00:46:32.680
[Guest]: report.

00:46:32.680 --> 00:46:41.680
[Guest]: The average monthly fee of private schools in UP comes around 250 rupees.

00:46:41.680 --> 00:46:47.800
[Guest]: And therefore, now if you will also identify, as I travel a lot, I also interact with auto

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:51.600
[Guest]: rickshaw drivers, taxi drivers, even cycle rickshaw pullers.

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:58.040
[Guest]: And I have found that even poorest of poor such as cycle rickshaw puller, today, he would

00:46:58.040 --> 00:47:06.120
[Guest]: prefer to skip a day's meal, but wants to send their children to a private school.

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:08.440
[Guest]: And certainly these are not elite private schools.

00:47:08.440 --> 00:47:11.760
[Guest]: These are those low cost private schools.

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:17.560
[Guest]: So I would not say it is only for rich, certainly because of several policy provisions that

00:47:17.560 --> 00:47:24.000
[Guest]: we talked, the cost happens to be inflated, which certainly through reforms could be brought

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:25.000
[Amit Varma]: down.

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:29.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and that's to me, it's a deeply poignant story that if someone who's earning three

00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:35.240
[Amit Varma]: or 4000 a month, you know, is his household income, and he cares deeply about his kids

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:39.960
[Amit Varma]: education, because he wants them to go beyond what he has managed to do in his life, and

00:47:39.960 --> 00:47:42.040
[Amit Varma]: he wants his kid to get an education.

00:47:42.040 --> 00:47:45.260
[Amit Varma]: But the free government schools which are set up for that are simply not doing that.

00:47:45.260 --> 00:47:49.080
[Amit Varma]: And he's actually paying money, which is a substantial amount of money for him to 50

00:47:49.080 --> 00:47:54.360
[Amit Varma]: may not seem anything for us or 500 may not seem anything for us, but for those people

00:47:54.360 --> 00:47:58.200
[Amit Varma]: is a substantial amount of money, but they're making that sacrifice, because it is their

00:47:58.200 --> 00:47:59.560
[Amit Varma]: only way out.

00:47:59.560 --> 00:48:03.320
[Amit Varma]: And then what they also see is that even those private schools that they send their kids

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:08.040
[Amit Varma]: to face these enormous, enormous challenges from the state itself.

00:48:08.040 --> 00:48:13.160
[Guest]: And like you pointed out, those are the schools being closed down, those are your even I come

00:48:13.160 --> 00:48:15.560
[Guest]: from a city called Banaras.

00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:21.680
[Guest]: And at my house, there is a maid and maids and her children to a private school.

00:48:21.680 --> 00:48:26.960
[Guest]: And that is the kind of schools being targeted now by the government, which I see completely

00:48:26.960 --> 00:48:29.120
[Amit Varma]: it's injustice, it's inhuman.

00:48:29.120 --> 00:48:33.680
[Amit Varma]: And you have 10s and 1000s of low cost private schools like that having to shut down because

00:48:33.680 --> 00:48:38.000
[Amit Varma]: of government regulations, despite the fact that they came up in the first place because

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:41.160
[Amit Varma]: the government had failed to provide that education.

00:48:41.160 --> 00:48:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And that just makes me so angry that I think that your term of anger for this, which is

00:48:46.080 --> 00:48:48.200
[Amit Varma]: fraud is not sufficient.

00:48:48.200 --> 00:48:50.160
[Amit Varma]: It's it's much worse than that.

00:48:50.160 --> 00:48:54.160
[Amit Varma]: It's a crime on the people of our country.

00:48:54.160 --> 00:48:58.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, a lot of these things, activists like yourself have been talking about for

00:48:58.720 --> 00:49:01.600
[Amit Varma]: a long time trying to raise awareness and so on.

00:49:01.600 --> 00:49:05.400
[Amit Varma]: And of course, parents of kids everywhere understand this, especially the poorer you

00:49:05.400 --> 00:49:08.080
[Amit Varma]: go, the more they understand how bad things are.

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:12.920
[Amit Varma]: For example, I was told of some statistic recently, some that's a more than 80% of government

00:49:12.920 --> 00:49:17.720
[Amit Varma]: school teachers send their children to private schools.

00:49:17.720 --> 00:49:23.960
[Guest]: You know, what better evidence you require than this, not only teachers, all the politicians

00:49:23.960 --> 00:49:29.640
[Guest]: even who advocate government schooling, they send their children to private schools and

00:49:29.640 --> 00:49:35.720
[Guest]: they also since the money and power and sources, they're sending their kids to foreign schools.

00:49:35.720 --> 00:49:40.320
[Guest]: So then they don't even have to teach here in the Indian curriculum.

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:41.320
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:49:41.320 --> 00:49:46.560
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and it's kind of obvious that the way this structure is a lot of interesting

00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:52.000
[Amit Varma]: ways towards moving towards a solution emerge and let's not discuss any of those individually.

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:58.280
[Amit Varma]: But in terms of let's talk about what in the political economy makes change so difficult,

00:49:58.280 --> 00:50:02.240
[Amit Varma]: like one thing you pointed out is that there are interest groups like government teachers

00:50:02.240 --> 00:50:06.520
[Amit Varma]: unions which hold a certain amount of power, and they lobby politicians and they don't

00:50:06.520 --> 00:50:07.720
[Amit Varma]: let it happen.

00:50:07.720 --> 00:50:13.320
[Amit Varma]: So can you shed some more light on the incentives in the political economy and the different

00:50:13.320 --> 00:50:14.920
[Amit Varma]: interest groups?

00:50:14.920 --> 00:50:19.560
[Amit Varma]: And also earlier, like you've spoken a bit about the politicization of education, but

00:50:19.560 --> 00:50:22.880
[Amit Varma]: you also mentioned bureaucratization of education.

00:50:22.880 --> 00:50:26.640
[Guest]: So can you expand on that as well a little bit?

00:50:26.640 --> 00:50:27.640
[Guest]: Sure.

00:50:27.640 --> 00:50:32.520
[Guest]: Let's come to that political economy thing first.

00:50:32.520 --> 00:50:38.600
[Guest]: A little difficult to explain it in a short time.

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:42.240
[Guest]: But I mean, I'll give you just snapshots.

00:50:42.240 --> 00:50:48.920
[Guest]: The first thing you could see is politicians, they also have to go by the public sentiment

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:57.960
[Guest]: and somehow, it's already built in public sentiment that there should be free education

00:50:57.960 --> 00:51:00.760
[Guest]: and therefore government could deliver it.

00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:04.600
[Guest]: However, everything is taxed and paid by citizens themselves.

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:10.560
[Guest]: But somehow there is this acceptance that free education should not be charged.

00:51:10.560 --> 00:51:16.440
[Guest]: Second, whomever is providing should not make profit out of it, be it private or government

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:23.040
[Guest]: or anyone else, but should do it for the purpose of charity.

00:51:23.040 --> 00:51:27.400
[Guest]: And therefore, for politicians who sincerely also want to bring change, it becomes too

00:51:27.400 --> 00:51:34.240
[Guest]: difficult because all of a sudden there will be many organizations, unions on street protesting

00:51:34.240 --> 00:51:40.280
[Guest]: against them that they are kind of privatizing or commercializing education or giving in

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:42.520
[Guest]: profit hands.

00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:44.680
[Guest]: So that makes itself difficult.

00:51:44.680 --> 00:51:45.680
[Guest]: That's first thing.

00:51:45.680 --> 00:51:53.560
[Guest]: Now, second thing, I would also doubt whether politicians are so interested in doing it

00:51:53.560 --> 00:52:02.320
[Guest]: for reasons and this parasite culture and the pressure groups that they have, with teacher

00:52:02.320 --> 00:52:06.480
[Guest]: unions or other lobby groups to reform it.

00:52:06.480 --> 00:52:14.480
[Guest]: Also, one thing has come to my notice is education or things like that happens to be a deliverable,

00:52:14.480 --> 00:52:17.200
[Guest]: the outcome of which will be shown in long term.

00:52:17.200 --> 00:52:23.080
[Guest]: So for an example, my parents decided to invest in my education and after 10-15 years only

00:52:23.080 --> 00:52:28.680
[Guest]: they can see outcome and when the tenure is only five years or something and it to make

00:52:28.680 --> 00:52:34.000
[Guest]: bureaucracy work and get a school sanction for any MLA or MP in the constituency will

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:36.040
[Guest]: take one, two, three years.

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:44.200
[Guest]: So the impact is not as visible and therefore, in my opinion, let's say even if I might be

00:52:44.200 --> 00:52:51.160
[Guest]: wrong too, but their interest is more into, let's say, building toilet or giving kumble

00:52:51.160 --> 00:52:56.080
[Guest]: or whatever, which is more of a photo opportunity that the MP MLA is doing something or cleaning

00:52:56.080 --> 00:52:59.040
[Guest]: road or whatever.

00:52:59.040 --> 00:53:05.120
[Guest]: So I don't really see that they are as interested.

00:53:05.120 --> 00:53:10.520
[Guest]: Any points that you think is more relevant?

00:53:10.520 --> 00:53:17.400
[Amit Varma]: I just want to say that I 100% agree with your opinion and this is one of the problems

00:53:17.400 --> 00:53:21.920
[Amit Varma]: you face with governance is that politicians are always focused on the short term and like

00:53:21.920 --> 00:53:25.960
[Amit Varma]: you correctly said, something like investments in anything that show results in the long

00:53:25.960 --> 00:53:30.360
[Amit Varma]: term, beyond the five-year term of a politician, therefore become pointless.

00:53:30.360 --> 00:53:36.640
[Amit Varma]: They are more interested in optics and photo opportunity, which a toilet shawl will provide

00:53:36.640 --> 00:53:42.520
[Amit Varma]: more than something that is more abstract, especially if it means withdrawing from the,

00:53:42.520 --> 00:53:45.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, removing restrictions on private schools.

00:53:45.120 --> 00:53:49.360
[Amit Varma]: The government servant can't then, there's nothing concrete for him to show too, because

00:53:49.360 --> 00:53:51.440
[Amit Varma]: it seems like, I mean, what have you done?

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:57.000
[Amit Varma]: But what you correctly pointed out earlier and something that makes me almost despair

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:03.160
[Amit Varma]: is this attitude that Indians have that whatever problems we have, the government is a solution.

00:54:03.160 --> 00:54:09.080
[Amit Varma]: People realizing that in cases like education, for example, the government is a problem.

00:54:09.080 --> 00:54:12.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one example I often kind of try to point out is that, you know, people

00:54:12.440 --> 00:54:16.000
[Amit Varma]: say that, look, education is so important, so the government has to do it.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:21.800
[Amit Varma]: And my reply to that always is that it is because education is so important and crucial

00:54:21.800 --> 00:54:25.920
[Amit Varma]: that the government must allow society to participate in it.

00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:33.320
[Amit Varma]: And like, I'm an 80s child and the classic analog I give is of telecom and airlines and

00:54:33.320 --> 00:54:37.240
[Amit Varma]: especially telecom, that those were government monopolies in the 80s, it took you five years

00:54:37.240 --> 00:54:41.040
[Amit Varma]: to get, you had a five year waiting list for a telephone and then private players were

00:54:41.040 --> 00:54:42.040
[Amit Varma]: allowed.

00:54:42.040 --> 00:54:46.120
[Amit Varma]: And if you go by the same rhetoric they give behind education, then you would expect the

00:54:46.120 --> 00:54:51.080
[Amit Varma]: quality to drop, the private players to exploit customers and the prices to be too high.

00:54:51.080 --> 00:54:55.760
[Amit Varma]: But instead, what you have is an explosion in quality because of competition and because

00:54:55.760 --> 00:54:57.200
[Amit Varma]: of those incentives.

00:54:57.200 --> 00:55:02.440
[Amit Varma]: And now today, the poorest of the poor have smartphones, even if they're not educated,

00:55:02.440 --> 00:55:06.820
[Amit Varma]: you know, and it's one of the great tragedies of our country.

00:55:06.820 --> 00:55:10.200
[Amit Varma]: And it makes me angrier and angrier as the years go by.

00:55:10.200 --> 00:55:15.520
[Guest]: And the students are able to understand English today because of mobile English keypad rather

00:55:15.520 --> 00:55:18.400
[Guest]: than going to school and understanding English.

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:25.640
[Guest]: Anyways, something that I also wanted to talk more because these days, the anger comes out

00:55:25.640 --> 00:55:30.800
[Guest]: is you did not contest my insight of education being fraud, otherwise they could have given

00:55:30.800 --> 00:55:31.800
[Amit Varma]: you several examples.

00:55:31.800 --> 00:55:36.880
[Amit Varma]: Let's imagine, I know, because I agree with you, but I know much less about why it is

00:55:36.880 --> 00:55:37.880
[Amit Varma]: a fraud.

00:55:37.880 --> 00:55:42.120
[Guest]: So let's assume for a moment that I have contested it, I have said, no, Amit is not a fraud.

00:55:42.120 --> 00:55:45.120
[Guest]: So why don't you elaborate?

00:55:45.120 --> 00:55:51.800
[Guest]: Because we started talking about government teachers also and how even they are victim.

00:55:51.800 --> 00:55:59.280
[Guest]: One of the things I can talk about is at the beginning of the session around March or April,

00:55:59.280 --> 00:56:06.840
[Guest]: try going to meet any of the education minister at the residence or office or education secretary

00:56:06.840 --> 00:56:09.640
[Guest]: in any of the state.

00:56:09.640 --> 00:56:13.120
[Guest]: What you'll find that there is a huge crowd.

00:56:13.120 --> 00:56:17.320
[Guest]: And you'll find most of the people in the crowd are teachers.

00:56:17.320 --> 00:56:24.120
[Guest]: Now these teachers are there lined up at the house of education minister.

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:31.040
[Guest]: And if you investigate into the reason, you'll find they're mainly asking for their transfer

00:56:31.040 --> 00:56:34.160
[Guest]: and posting.

00:56:34.160 --> 00:56:39.120
[Guest]: And then certainly minister would do whatever formally has to do.

00:56:39.120 --> 00:56:46.120
[Guest]: There will be a guy, more like an agent or mediator or whomever you call it, would be

00:56:46.120 --> 00:56:49.240
[Guest]: there who would then deal with them.

00:56:49.240 --> 00:56:52.680
[Guest]: So fix up a certain price and that.

00:56:52.680 --> 00:56:56.960
[Guest]: So if you pay, then you will get your desired postings, etc.

00:56:56.960 --> 00:56:57.960
[Guest]: Right.

00:56:57.960 --> 00:57:00.880
[Guest]: That itself has become a massive fraud.

00:57:00.880 --> 00:57:06.000
[Guest]: At places though, this was being done at a secretary level.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:09.160
[Guest]: Then ministers realized that we are losing money that we can make.

00:57:09.160 --> 00:57:16.200
[Guest]: So ministers have taken, in some states, lets me, I hope I go back home, as chief minister

00:57:16.200 --> 00:57:19.320
[Guest]: realized that there is enough to make.

00:57:19.320 --> 00:57:25.520
[Guest]: Those kind of people don't listen to this podcast, so don't worry about that.

00:57:25.520 --> 00:57:34.520
[Guest]: At times, I remember at some education minister office that I had gone to meet, and a teacher

00:57:34.520 --> 00:57:36.160
[Guest]: walked in for the same request.

00:57:36.160 --> 00:57:39.840
[Guest]: And he says, no, no, now chief minister is looking directly at us.

00:57:39.840 --> 00:57:42.920
[Amit Varma]: So it's become so lucrative.

00:57:42.920 --> 00:57:44.000
[Guest]: Right.

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:47.960
[Guest]: So that is the kind of day to day examples that you get.

00:57:47.960 --> 00:57:53.120
[Guest]: And then you think of, do we as a country have some hope?

00:57:53.120 --> 00:57:57.120
[Amit Varma]: So you're someone who's not only been a researcher and shredded all this, but you've also been

00:57:57.120 --> 00:58:00.720
[Amit Varma]: an activist and you've tried to bring about change.

00:58:00.720 --> 00:58:14.120
[Guest]: I mean, you are in a sense, the other big thing happens in your marks inflation, right?

00:58:14.120 --> 00:58:19.360
[Guest]: So there are boards, education board, each state has education board and CBSE, ICSE and

00:58:19.360 --> 00:58:21.480
[Guest]: IG and all of that.

00:58:21.480 --> 00:58:28.840
[Guest]: Specifically, one fraud thing started with the evolution of CBSE itself.

00:58:28.840 --> 00:58:37.320
[Guest]: So if you remember, I, as I said, I'm from UP, I went to a state affiliated board school.

00:58:37.320 --> 00:58:45.040
[Guest]: So at our age, at that time, there was this chief minister called Kalyan Singh, right?

00:58:45.040 --> 00:58:51.800
[Guest]: And people say I passed high school or intermediate in Kalyan Singh's regime, which means before

00:58:51.800 --> 00:58:58.920
[Guest]: that was Mulayam Singh and at the Mulayam Singh time, they were very generous and liberal

00:58:58.920 --> 00:58:59.920
[Guest]: with cheating approach.

00:58:59.920 --> 00:59:05.160
[Guest]: You know, today, you can see Bihar, the massive, you know, cheating their parents or friends

00:59:05.160 --> 00:59:08.360
[Guest]: who are helping them to copy.

00:59:08.360 --> 00:59:11.580
[Guest]: So that used to happen and therefore Kalyan Singh.

00:59:11.580 --> 00:59:17.560
[Guest]: So on what the main point I want to come to, on an average, if you see the result every

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:24.200
[Guest]: year would be 30%, 40%, maximum 50% students who have passed.

00:59:24.200 --> 00:59:30.240
[Guest]: And the topper of the state would have 82%, 83%, right?

00:59:30.240 --> 00:59:36.600
[Guest]: Now, then CBSE came in and CBSE had a different marking pattern.

00:59:36.600 --> 00:59:41.720
[Guest]: And therefore, the similar kind of average student like me, if I'm getting 50% marks

00:59:41.720 --> 00:59:49.160
[Guest]: in state board, I would get 65 or 70% mark in CBSE board, right?

00:59:49.160 --> 00:59:57.880
[Guest]: Slowly that state realized that all of these CBSE students are easily getting admission

00:59:57.880 --> 01:00:04.280
[Guest]: later on in, let's say, Delhi University or whatever university for college.

01:00:04.280 --> 01:00:07.200
[Guest]: And our students are not finding admission.

01:00:07.200 --> 01:00:14.080
[Guest]: If the admission is based on your high school and enter marks, and therefore they also started

01:00:14.080 --> 01:00:19.600
[Guest]: figuring out other ways of inflating the mark, inflating or changing the marking pattern

01:00:19.600 --> 01:00:22.720
[Guest]: so that students get more marks.

01:00:22.720 --> 01:00:26.240
[Guest]: There happens to be one more dynamics here.

01:00:26.240 --> 01:00:32.800
[Guest]: So every time, and let's say as an education minister, I want to show my performance that

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:40.000
[Guest]: I have done very good in education segment or like we recently, last year in Punjab,

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:47.840
[Guest]: the education secretary was expelled, he was fired because of the poor percentage of result.

01:00:47.840 --> 01:00:53.400
[Guest]: So you want to show that earlier, 50% students used to pass, we have improved so much that

01:00:53.400 --> 01:00:55.680
[Guest]: 70% students are passing, right?

01:00:55.680 --> 01:00:59.560
[Guest]: Something similar is happening in Delhi also, currently they're debating, our students

01:00:59.560 --> 01:01:03.080
[Guest]: are performing very well, right?

01:01:03.080 --> 01:01:07.480
[Guest]: I won't get into that Delhi debate, I can get into that separately.

01:01:07.480 --> 01:01:13.920
[Guest]: But states are also inflating, state boards are inflating marks to show that we are doing

01:01:13.920 --> 01:01:14.920
[Guest]: a good job.

01:01:14.920 --> 01:01:15.920
[Guest]: Students are studying more.

01:01:15.920 --> 01:01:20.000
[Guest]: Look, the results of this government school are also coming out very well.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:26.080
[Guest]: And even CBSE adopted this system, what they called it, moderation system.

01:01:26.080 --> 01:01:34.600
[Guest]: So they figured out scientifically and justified ways of giving you more and more marks.

01:01:34.600 --> 01:01:36.600
[Guest]: That is another level of fraud happening.

01:01:36.600 --> 01:01:41.640
[Amit Varma]: And then we say, okay, the kid looks dumb, but he has 90% marks.

01:01:41.640 --> 01:01:48.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I remember back in the day in my 10th and 12th, I got like around 70% and my now

01:01:48.320 --> 01:01:50.120
[Amit Varma]: wife got a little more than me.

01:01:50.120 --> 01:01:53.960
[Amit Varma]: And we were just talking like a couple of days back that boss, in today's time, we would

01:01:53.960 --> 01:01:57.040
[Amit Varma]: have got admission nowhere, we are finished.

01:01:57.040 --> 01:02:05.960
[Guest]: In Delhi, something like since Stephen College, they got 100% students with 100% marks as

01:02:05.960 --> 01:02:06.960
[Guest]: admission.

01:02:06.960 --> 01:02:10.320
[Guest]: So even you have 99, you're not going to get admission.

01:02:10.320 --> 01:02:12.080
[Guest]: So think about it.

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:21.160
[Guest]: Now why is that as an activist or as a solution, if we start thinking about it, is because

01:02:21.160 --> 01:02:27.600
[Guest]: the producer, when you design or produce is who, the same government, when the assessment

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:32.160
[Guest]: is happening, it's the same government, when the outcome has to be shown, it's the same

01:02:32.160 --> 01:02:33.160
[Guest]: government.

01:02:33.160 --> 01:02:38.800
[Guest]: So as long as I monitor myself, I would give all good marks, I'll say I'm the best person

01:02:38.800 --> 01:02:41.960
[Guest]: even better than Narendra Modi, right?

01:02:41.960 --> 01:02:42.960
[Amit Varma]: And that is what is happening.

01:02:42.960 --> 01:02:46.040
[Amit Varma]: Be careful what you say.

01:02:46.040 --> 01:02:50.640
[Guest]: Not that kind of audience listens to your podcast anyway, right?

01:02:50.640 --> 01:02:53.960
[Guest]: I mean, whomsoever.

01:02:53.960 --> 01:03:00.920
[Guest]: So you need to bring some level of accountability and transparency in the system, otherwise.

01:03:00.920 --> 01:03:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's a great insight.

01:03:01.920 --> 01:03:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Again, to go back to the question of incentives, the government is the provider, the government

01:03:08.440 --> 01:03:13.600
[Amit Varma]: is also the person who is ranking the quality of the provision, financing and financing

01:03:13.600 --> 01:03:19.120
[Amit Varma]: the provision and everything, whereas, you know, in a regular market system, what you

01:03:19.120 --> 01:03:22.720
[Amit Varma]: would really have is that it's the parents who decide, the people who are, and therefore

01:03:22.720 --> 01:03:25.360
[Amit Varma]: they keep the system sort of accountable.

01:03:25.360 --> 01:03:29.360
[Guest]: So, they don't take anything from the consumer, they don't get any assessment from the parents,

01:03:29.360 --> 01:03:32.960
[Guest]: they don't get any assessment from the children, how good is the teacher, how good is the infrastructure,

01:03:32.960 --> 01:03:34.520
[Amit Varma]: how good is your education minister.

01:03:34.520 --> 01:03:38.040
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, the fact that so many poor parents vote with their feet and take their

01:03:38.040 --> 01:03:43.560
[Amit Varma]: children to budget private schools, is itself them assessing the state of education and

01:03:43.560 --> 01:03:47.960
[Amit Varma]: the state then reacts by shutting down as many of those private schools as it can.

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:52.800
[Amit Varma]: And the other tragic point that you just pointed out, and which is, again, a great insight

01:03:52.800 --> 01:03:58.160
[Amit Varma]: I'd like to call attention to, is the relation between optics and performance.

01:03:58.160 --> 01:04:02.280
[Amit Varma]: And that's not, I mean, it is in the nature of governments and the parties that are ruling

01:04:02.280 --> 01:04:07.160
[Amit Varma]: the governments at any time, that their incentive is not really to perform because no one's

01:04:07.160 --> 01:04:08.520
[Amit Varma]: holding them accountable.

01:04:08.520 --> 01:04:12.680
[Amit Varma]: But their incentive is to focus on optics like, look, so many kids have passed and it's

01:04:12.680 --> 01:04:16.560
[Amit Varma]: more than last time, because they want to get re-elected.

01:04:16.560 --> 01:04:19.240
[Amit Varma]: And again, the incentives are completely destroyed.

01:04:19.240 --> 01:04:25.680
[Amit Varma]: But the question I sort of want to ask is that, you've not only, you know, done a lot

01:04:25.680 --> 01:04:30.600
[Amit Varma]: of research and gained a lot of insight into this field, but you've also been an activist

01:04:30.600 --> 01:04:35.880
[Amit Varma]: and a very passionate activist who's, you know, you meet politicians all the time, you

01:04:35.880 --> 01:04:37.720
[Amit Varma]: meet bureaucrats all the time.

01:04:37.720 --> 01:04:42.920
[Amit Varma]: So my two part question is that, what level of acceptance is there among these individuals

01:04:42.920 --> 01:04:47.320
[Amit Varma]: in government, you know, outside of their roles and their incentives, that there is

01:04:47.320 --> 01:04:50.840
[Amit Varma]: a problem and that, you know, that it has to be fixed?

01:04:50.840 --> 01:04:51.840
[Amit Varma]: That's part one.

01:04:51.840 --> 01:04:57.800
[Amit Varma]: And part two is that going beyond this acceptance of, going beyond this recognition of the problem,

01:04:57.800 --> 01:05:04.120
[Amit Varma]: has there been any movement towards a solution in all the time that you've been working?

01:05:04.120 --> 01:05:06.680
[Guest]: This is a difficult one.

01:05:06.680 --> 01:05:16.120
[Guest]: Because to answer this, I will have to decode all of these conversations that I have with

01:05:16.120 --> 01:05:21.400
[Guest]: politicians and policy makers and, and I'll have to base my judgment on that everything

01:05:21.400 --> 01:05:23.720
[Guest]: that they're saying is sincere and true.

01:05:23.720 --> 01:05:28.240
[Guest]: Yeah, which you have a sense of whether it's not by...

01:05:28.240 --> 01:05:35.400
[Guest]: So I do think that in a certain level and within the government also they realize.

01:05:35.400 --> 01:05:42.640
[Guest]: So number one, because they have designed and they are doing it, they know it.

01:05:42.640 --> 01:05:48.400
[Guest]: But as I said, the major, major challenge for education sector happens to be this public

01:05:48.400 --> 01:05:54.480
[Guest]: sentiment itself, the moment that is changed, or politicians get a sense that people are

01:05:54.480 --> 01:05:55.480
[Guest]: open for change.

01:05:55.480 --> 01:06:02.320
[Guest]: And if by bringing some sort of reform, I would not be thrown out of office, they would

01:06:02.320 --> 01:06:04.480
[Guest]: be open to it.

01:06:04.480 --> 01:06:11.480
[Guest]: The other way of thinking is until it becomes inevitable.

01:06:11.480 --> 01:06:19.960
[Guest]: I know with my conversation with people, formally and informally, they, whenever they have realized,

01:06:19.960 --> 01:06:28.760
[Guest]: in fact, we had, I personally had high hope with this current MHRD minister and the secretary

01:06:28.760 --> 01:06:30.720
[Guest]: also.

01:06:30.720 --> 01:06:37.960
[Guest]: And specifically the secretary, however, I'm deeply, deeply disappointed, is they realize

01:06:37.960 --> 01:06:47.320
[Guest]: it and they were trying to look for political viability of bringing some of those reforms.

01:06:47.320 --> 01:06:52.920
[Guest]: Specifically you, so within government, there are segments, something like Niti Aayog, Niti

01:06:52.920 --> 01:06:55.720
[Guest]: Aayog published its three years action plan.

01:06:55.720 --> 01:07:00.000
[Guest]: And within there, there is a section on school education.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:04.760
[Guest]: And they have proposed some good ideas.

01:07:04.760 --> 01:07:10.320
[Guest]: But it's difficult at the moment.

01:07:10.320 --> 01:07:15.560
[Guest]: Also I understand their challenge too, for currently BJP led government.

01:07:15.560 --> 01:07:20.280
[Guest]: No matter what they do, the moment they touch education, everyone, opposition, etc., comes

01:07:20.280 --> 01:07:24.320
[Guest]: in as a saffronizing education, or commercializing education.

01:07:24.320 --> 01:07:29.960
[Guest]: And for that they have also, so if you know, twice they constituted committee for national

01:07:29.960 --> 01:07:37.320
[Guest]: education policy, and yet they have not progressed on it.

01:07:37.320 --> 01:07:42.960
[Guest]: I can't comment on future, but today or tomorrow, it's going to become inevitable and they will

01:07:42.960 --> 01:07:49.560
[Guest]: have to do it because there is no other way than saving truth by accepting the truth.

01:07:49.560 --> 01:07:50.560
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:07:50.560 --> 01:07:55.600
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, this has been an incredibly insightful episode and I want to end by asking

01:07:55.600 --> 01:07:56.600
[Amit Varma]: you two questions.

01:07:56.600 --> 01:08:01.800
[Amit Varma]: I ask all my guests on whatever subject they're talking about at that point in time, and those

01:08:01.800 --> 01:08:08.360
[Amit Varma]: two questions are, what makes you despair about what is happening to education in this

01:08:08.360 --> 01:08:09.360
[Amit Varma]: country?

01:08:09.360 --> 01:08:10.880
[Amit Varma]: And what gives you hope?

01:08:10.880 --> 01:08:15.500
[Guest]: Once again, these are difficult questions.

01:08:15.500 --> 01:08:23.000
[Guest]: So something is why I got into it and still investing my time and energy, even it's very

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:32.440
[Guest]: frustrating thing to do, is we ourselves have gone through this system.

01:08:32.440 --> 01:08:37.520
[Guest]: At times I feel that it was good to be a backbencher because the system could corrupt me less.

01:08:37.520 --> 01:08:40.960
[Guest]: All of those in the front were highly corrupted.

01:08:40.960 --> 01:08:45.000
[Guest]: I was also a backbencher.

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:50.440
[Guest]: And I have seen many of our own friends and colleagues or relatives or cousins struggling

01:08:50.440 --> 01:08:53.520
[Guest]: with it, or even today.

01:08:53.520 --> 01:08:59.880
[Guest]: And that makes me work on it, frankly speaking, that...

01:08:59.880 --> 01:09:02.600
[Amit Varma]: You feel you have no choice, you owe this to...

01:09:02.600 --> 01:09:09.500
[Guest]: We have to, because the, I mean, the pain I have seen people going through of unnecessarily,

01:09:09.500 --> 01:09:14.920
[Guest]: for an example, let's say, parents scolding or relatives scolding for bringing lesser

01:09:14.920 --> 01:09:18.240
[Guest]: marks than 70% or 90% or why not to study.

01:09:18.240 --> 01:09:25.120
[Guest]: I mean, this study thing has become such a, I don't know what to call it, a big burden

